# Work

Drive a single plan task to completion. The task runs inside a fresh `worker` subagent so the main context stays lean; the main context only orchestrates (claim → spawn worker → verify done).

The tier (reasoning effort) and model were both chosen at planning time and are persisted on the task. The launcher (autopilot / `keeper dispatch`) resolves the task's `{model, effort}` cell producer-side and selects the matching `work` plugin at launch via `--plugin-dir`, so the session running this skill already has exactly ONE `work` plugin loaded — the per-cell `worker` agent baked with that model + effort. This skill therefore spawns the CONSTANT `work:worker` subagent; it never picks, composes, or selects the tier/model itself. `claim` still emits a `worker_agent` field whose null-ness (either axis unset) is the hard-stop gate — the skill reads only that null-ness, never the value.

## When to invoke

The human said "work", "/work", or passed an existing plan task id to run. Accepts a single input shape:

- `fn-N-slug.M` — task id, run just this one task

---

## Phase 1 — Claim the task

**Shared-tree principle (read first):** This repo runs concurrent agents and the human's in-progress work in parallel — at any moment the working tree may carry uncommitted changes that have nothing to do with this task. Any file you didn't write through this session belongs to someone else: never classify it as in-/out-of-scope for the worker, never commit it. Never run mutating `git stash` either — refs/stash is ONE repo-global stack shared by every sibling worktree and the human's checkout, so a worker's stash push/pop displaces files across trees; the branch-guard hook hard-denies it (list/show/create stay available). For file-level undo use `git restore <path>`; to park work make a temp commit, never stash. The sanctioned way a worker answers "is this failing test pre-existing at the base, or did I cause it?" is `keeper baseline <base sha> --wait` (keyed on the task-start `head_sha`), never a stash-and-rerun — and a test green at the baseline but red in the worktree points at that worktree's environment, not the base. Authoritative attribution comes from `keeper session state`'s `session_files` field (subagent writes share the parent session_id, so the orchestrator's session_files already covers worker output) — anything in `status_porcelain` but not in `session_files` is someone else's territory.

One call asserts invariants, claims the task (`todo` → `in_progress`), and returns the full worker briefing — no `detect`, no separate `show`/`cat`, no `cd`. `claim` resolves the owning project cwd-agnostically (scans configured `roots`), so this works from any directory:

```bash
keeper plan claim <task_id>
```

**On a typed error** — envelope `{"success": false, "error": {"code", "message", "details"}}` — surface `error.message` verbatim and stop. The `code` covers every reject (`BAD_TASK_ID`, `TASK_NOT_FOUND`, `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID`, `TASK_DONE`, `TASK_BLOCKED`, claimed-by-another, unmet deps). `claim` fails loud on bad input — automation always supplies a valid id, so there's no empty-args branch to handle. For an `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID` (same id in multiple projects), re-run with `keeper plan claim <task_id> --project <path>`.

**On success**, read the briefing envelope and pin these in working memory for the phases below:

- `task_id`, `epic_id` — ids.
- `target_repo` — absolute path the worker cds into for code work (may equal `primary_repo` for single-repo tasks).
- `primary_repo` — absolute path of the plan state repo (where the `.keeper/` commit lands).
- `tier` — persisted tier (`medium | high | xhigh | max`). This skill quotes it back for transparency but never picks it.
- `worker_model` — persisted model (the model axis of the `{model × effort}` cell). Quoted back for transparency, never picked here.
- `worker_agent` — the null-gate signal `claim` derives from the tier + model: non-null when both axes are set, or `null` when either is unset (a legacy task that never carried a tier or a model). The spawn target is the constant `work:worker`, decoupled from this value; a `null` value is a hard stop (see Phase 2a).
- `task_state`, `epic_state` — runtime + epic metadata (status, title).
- `brief_ref` — absolute path to the worker's brief JSON (`<primary_repo>/.keeper/state/briefs/<task_id>.json`). `claim` wrote the task spec and epic spec into this file out-of-band; you pass the handle to the worker, which reads it itself. This skill never opens the brief — it is content-blind.

Quote back a one-line summary so the human sees state is loaded, naming the persisted model + tier for transparency: *"working `fn-1-foo.3` at `<worker_model>`/`<tier>`: <title>."*

---

## Phase 2 — Run task

The task is already claimed and the briefing is in working memory (Phase 1). The worker spawns into `target_repo` from the envelope.

### 2a. Spawn worker subagent

Use the Task tool to invoke the constant `work:worker` subagent with a minimal config-only prompt. The worker's shared body lives in `template/agents/worker.md.tmpl` (rendered per `{model × effort}` cell into `workers/<model>-<effort>/agents/worker.md`, manifest name `work`); the launcher selected exactly one such cell at launch via `--plugin-dir`, so `work:worker` resolves to the tier-matched worker. Do **not** paraphrase those phases here.

**Null-axis stop.** If the envelope's `worker_agent` is `null` (a legacy task missing a tier or a model), do **not** spawn — surface the typed stop *"tier or model unset — remediate via /plan:plan <epic_id> refine"* verbatim and stop. The skill never invents a tier/model or spawns a worker for an unset axis.

**Tier + model are already chosen** (see the intro) — this skill never picks or persists either. The launcher already selected the matching `work` cell at launch; the cell's `worker` agent file owns the model + `effort:`. Spawn the constant `work:worker`, no `model=`.

**Content-blind spawn.** This skill never inlines spec prose into the worker prompt — `claim` already wrote the task spec and epic spec into the brief JSON at `brief_ref`. You pass the worker only config lines, including `BRIEF_REF`; the worker reads the brief itself in its Phase 1.

**Prompt template:**

```
Implement a plan task.

TASK_ID: <fn-N-slug.M>
EPIC_ID: <fn-N-slug>
PLAN_CLI: keeper plan
TARGET_REPO: <absolute path to target_repo, or same as PRIMARY_REPO if task.target_repo is null>
PRIMARY_REPO: <absolute path to the primary_repo (plan state repo)>
BRIEF_REF: <absolute path from the Phase 1 claim envelope's brief_ref>

## Task

Follow your agent spec. Read BRIEF_REF in Phase 1 to get the task spec and epic spec. If your turn opens with a directive from this skill instead of this template, the directive overrides the phase scaffolding.
```

The prompt is config-only — no prose blocks. The worker's Phase 1 reads the brief from `BRIEF_REF` (parsing `task_spec_md` / `epic_spec_md`) and self-checks its identity against the brief, so the orchestrator carries no spec content in its own context.

Populate `TARGET_REPO`, `PRIMARY_REPO`, and `BRIEF_REF` directly from the Phase 1 claim envelope — all are already fully resolved to absolute paths:
- `TARGET_REPO` — the envelope's `target_repo`.
- `PRIMARY_REPO` — the envelope's `primary_repo`.
- `BRIEF_REF` — the envelope's `brief_ref`.

Invocation:

```
Task(
    subagent_type="work:worker",
    description="Work <task_id>",
    prompt="<prompt above>"
)
```

`subagent_type` is the constant string `work:worker` — the launcher loaded exactly one `work` plugin (the tier-matched cell) at launch, so `work:worker` resolves to it directly. Do **not** pass `model=` on the spawn — the cell's agent file owns the model and effort. The worker returns a capped summary (5 template lines plus at most 3 note lines: what was implemented, files changed, tests run). Don't re-read files the worker already touched — trust the return value.

**Capture `worker_agent_id` from the Task tool result.** The result string ends with `…agentId: <hex> (use SendMessage with to: '<id>' to continue this agent)`. Extract with the regex `agentId:\s*([a-f0-9]{10,})` (the agent_id has no newline before it — `re.search`, not `re.match`). Pin the captured hex string in working memory as `worker_agent_id` for Phase 2b's warm-resume path. If the regex doesn't match (very rare), set `worker_agent_id = None` and continue — Phase 2b's cold path handles missing-id case.

### 2b. Reconcile and switch

After the worker returns, collapse the entire post-worker assessment into ONE read-only call:

```bash
keeper plan reconcile <task_id>
```

`reconcile` computes a typed verdict from plan-native data alone — merged status, trailer-authentic source commits (against `target_repo` + `epic.touched_repos`), HEAD-visibility of the committed task JSON (against `state_repo`), and an epic tally. NO keeper call, no `keeper plan show`, no `keeper find-task-commit`, no `keeper session state`, no `validate --epic`, no git-porcelain reasoning. Delivery cleanliness is the worker's own job — it runs a mandatory `keeper session state` self-check on every path and commits its session files before returning, so the orchestrator never reasons over attribution.

**On a typed error** — envelope `{"success": false, "error": {"code", "message", "details"}}` (`BAD_TASK_ID`, `TASK_NOT_FOUND`, `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID`) — surface `error.message` verbatim and stop. For `AMBIGUOUS_TASK_ID`, re-run with `keeper plan reconcile <task_id> --project <path>`.

**On success**, read the envelope `{verdict, task_id, epic_id, status, source_commits, state_head_visible, dirty_session_files, epic_progress, assessed_at, blocked_reason}` and switch on `verdict`. The switch is total over all seven verdicts. `dirty_session_files` is the close-out gate's observable — a count of undischarged files in the worker's lane, or `null` when git was unreadable (a fail-open marker); the stop-guard family reads it, the orchestrator switch does not.

**Every non-`done` verdict is a resume directive, never a work order.** A dirty tree, failing lint, or a missing commit is the worker's to fix in the worker's context — you route the nudge back into the worker and never touch the tree yourself. The global commit-by-default convention does not apply to this skill: it never edits, so it never commits. The switch arms:

- **`done`** → the source commit and the `.keeper/` state commit both landed. Continue to Phase 3 (report).
- **`in_progress_committed`** → the worker's source commit landed but `keeper plan done` never fired. Resume with the nudge *"Source commit `<sha>` landed for `<id>` (sha from `source_commits[0]`) — run `keeper plan done <task_id> --summary "..."` now."*
- **`in_progress_uncommitted`** → the worker dropped before committing. Resume with the nudge *"Finish implementation, run tests within your two-full-pass budget, `keeper commit-work`, `keeper plan done`."*
- **`state_uncommitted`** → the worker stamped `done` but the `.keeper/` state commit never landed. Resume with the nudge *"Re-run `keeper plan done <task_id> --summary "..."` to land the state commit."*
- **`blocked`** → the worker escalated a semantic block; the task already carries the block on the board → **Phase 2c** (stamp-if-needed, then surface-and-stop). Carry the `blocked_reason` plus any `BLOCKED: <category>` breadcrumb from the worker return into Phase 2c.
- **`not_started`** → unexpected post-worker (the task is still `todo`); surface the verdict verbatim and stop.
- **`tooling_error`** → a git subprocess failed and the verdict is unreliable; surface the envelope verbatim and stop. **Do NOT act on a `tooling_error`** — fail closed, never resume against an unreliable verdict.

**Resume machinery** (the three `in_progress_*` / `state_uncommitted` arms). Recovery budget is **5 attempts (1 spawn + 4 retries)**; each warm resume or cold respawn counts one. The budget is best-effort per-invocation — warm retries live in an in-memory counter scoped to this invocation; nothing is persisted on the task. A separate `/plan:work` run that opens on an in-flight task can't see prior attempts, so each cold-resume run gets its own budget. A task that genuinely can't progress just keeps surfacing — the human eyeballs the pattern and blocks it by hand.

**Warm vs cold:** `worker_agent_id` captured in Phase 2a *this invocation* → in-session, go **warm**. Unset (Phase 2a didn't run this invocation but Phase 2b sees a non-`done` verdict) → cross-session, go **cold**.

**Warm path (in-session, `worker_agent_id` set):**

1. Build a tight resume directive from the arm's nudge above — process facts only, no spec prose. Carry `BRIEF_REF` (the Phase 1 `brief_ref`) so the worker can re-read context if it needs to. The worker's agent spec already says "resume directives outrank phases" and "do not re-anchor" — don't repeat those. Keep the directive a one-liner naming the next concrete action.

2. Send the directive (fire-and-forget — returns immediately):

   ```
   SendMessage(to=worker_agent_id, message=<directive>)
   ```

   SendMessage error envelope `{"success": false, "message": "No agent named '<id>' is currently addressable..."}` means the agent_id is dead/invalid — fall through to the cold path.

3. Wait for the worker to finish, then re-run `keeper plan reconcile <task_id>` and re-switch. On `done` → continue to Phase 3. On `blocked` → BLOCKED short-circuit. If the verdict is still a non-`done` `in_progress_*` / `state_uncommitted` arm, increment the invocation-local attempt counter and loop: re-send a fresh resume directive (warm) as long as `worker_agent_id` is still addressable, falling through to the cold path on a SendMessage error. Only after the **5th** attempt in this invocation drops do you `keeper plan block <task_id> --reason "RESUME_EXHAUSTED: harness dropped through 5 attempts (1 spawn + 4 retries) on Phase 2b resume"` and stop.

**Cold path (cross-session, or warm SendMessage error):**

1. Shell `keeper plan worker resume <task_id>` once. It regenerates the brief fresh and returns a typed envelope — read these fields: `worker_agent` (the null-gate signal — non-null when both axes are set, or `null` for a legacy task missing a tier or a model), `worker_model` (the persisted model axis), `brief_ref` (path to the freshly-baked brief), `nudge` (a one-line process-fact summary), `target_repo`, `primary_repo`, plus process facts `status`, `source_commit_sha`, `dirty_session_file_count`. There is no narrative `prompt` field — assemble the spawn prompt yourself from the config lines below. If `worker_agent` is `null`, surface the typed stop *"tier or model unset — remediate via /plan:plan <epic_id> refine"* and stop instead of spawning.

2. Spawn ONE fresh worker (the constant `work:worker`) with a config-only prompt carrying `BRIEF_REF` and the resume `nudge`:

   ```
   Task(
       subagent_type="work:worker",
       description="Resume <task_id>",
       prompt="Resume a plan task.\n\nTASK_ID: <task_id>\nEPIC_ID: <epic_id>\nPLAN_CLI: keeper plan\nTARGET_REPO: <envelope target_repo>\nPRIMARY_REPO: <envelope primary_repo>\nBRIEF_REF: <envelope brief_ref>\n\n## Task\n\n<envelope nudge> Follow your agent spec; read BRIEF_REF in Phase 1.",
   )
   ```

   `subagent_type` is the constant string `work:worker` — the launcher loaded the tier-matched cell at launch, so it resolves directly. No `model=` kwarg — the cell's agent file owns the model. The prompt carries process facts only (via the `nudge`) plus `BRIEF_REF` — no spec prose. The "harness-dropped predecessor" branch inside the worker agent spec's Phase 1 handles detection (it decides whether to skip ahead to `keeper plan done` or continue from implementation).

3. Re-run `keeper plan reconcile <task_id>` after the spawn returns and re-switch:
   - `done` → continue to Phase 3.
   - `blocked` → BLOCKED short-circuit.
   - a non-`done` `in_progress_*` / `state_uncommitted` arm (the cold spawn dropped) → this cold-resume invocation has spent its single attempt. The cold path holds no cross-invocation counter, so do NOT block — surface the verdict verbatim and stop. A fresh `/plan:work` re-run takes another attempt under the best-effort budget; a task that genuinely can't progress surfaces repeatedly and the human blocks it by hand.

**`BLOCKED:` short-circuit:** if the worker returns a `BLOCKED: <category>` message at any point, stamp the block and stop — route to **Phase 2c**. Semantic failures bypass the `in_progress_*` recovery flow entirely.

### 2c. Stamp the block and stop

Both semantic-block exits — the `blocked` reconcile verdict and the `BLOCKED: <category>` short-circuit — funnel here. The wielder's only job on a semantic block is to record it on the board and surface it; the daemon owns escalation from there. The wielder NEVER edits code, sends on the bus, or resumes the worker.

**Step 1 — stamp the block (if not already blocked).** If the task is not already `blocked` (the `BLOCKED:` short-circuit path — reconcile read a non-`blocked` verdict, or the worker returned a `BLOCKED:` breadcrumb mid-flight), stamp it:

```bash
keeper plan block <task_id> --reason "<CATEGORY>: <one-line text>"
```

Format the reason with the worker's `BLOCKED: <category>` category as the prefix (`SPEC_UNCLEAR: …`, `DEPENDENCY_BLOCKED: …`, etc.) — the daemon's escalation producer parses this category prefix and skips `TOOLING_FAILURE`. If the task is ALREADY `blocked` (the `blocked` reconcile verdict — the board already carries the reason), do not re-stamp.

**Step 2 — surface and stop.** Surface the `BLOCKED: <category>` breadcrumb plus the `blocked_reason` verbatim, then STOP. The daemon detects the blocked task on the board and escalates to the epic's `planner@<epic>` over the Agent Bus exactly once per block. This orchestrator session ends its turn but stays REACHABLE — its `keeper bus watch` inbox Monitor is armed. The planner resolves the blocker, runs `keeper plan unblock <task>`, and then bus-messages THIS session at its `work::<task>` name to resume (the PRIMARY path). On that resume directive, confirm the task is unblocked with `keeper plan reconcile <task>`, then re-enter the **Phase 2b** warm-resume: `SendMessage` the original worker subagent, cold-spawning a fresh subagent in-session only if that misses. The wielder still NEVER sends on the bus and never resumes on its own — it only RECEIVES the planner's resume and acts. Autopilot cold-re-dispatch is the fallback for when THIS orchestrator session is gone.

---

## Phase 3 — Report

The worker commits source (`keeper commit-work`) before stamping `keeper plan done`, and self-checks its own delivery cleanliness (its session files committed) before returning — so a `done` verdict in Phase 2b means both commits landed and nothing of the worker's is left dirty. The orchestrator never commits source, never runs `keeper plan done`, and never inspects git porcelain.

**Do NOT close the epic** — the orchestrator never closes; closing is a separate automated step. **`keeper commit-work` failures surface as BLOCKED** — a lint/commit/push failure makes the worker return `BLOCKED: TOOLING_FAILURE` with the verbatim envelope (Phase 2b's BLOCKED short-circuit catches it); the resume path picks up via the non-`done` verdict.

One-line summary, using `reconcile`'s `epic_progress` and the worker's returned commit sha:

> `fn-1-foo.3` done. commit: `<sha>`. epic progress: M/N tasks done.

Include the per-task commit sha from the worker return and `epic_progress.done` / `epic_progress.total` from the final `reconcile` envelope. No menu, no follow-up prompts.

